Analysis.name: Maternal sepsis
Bias.arising.from.the.randomization.proc:
• Participants assignment to intervention (the 'intention-to-treat' effect)
  • Described as 'randomised, double-blind, placebo-controlled trial' 
  • 829 women randomly assigned (1:1)

Analysis.name: Maternal sepsis
Bias.arising.from.the.randomization.proc: The sequential randomization assignments were computer generated using permuted block sizes of 3, 6, and 9, and were stratified by site.

Analysis.name: Maternal sepsis
Bias.arising.from.the.randomization.proc: "Trial packs of azithromycin and identical placebo were numbered sequentially with the use of a compyter algorithm, which used a predetermined 1:1 randomization schedule for azithromycin and placebo, stratified according to site, and a permuted-block randomization with vaaried block sizes." There was no clear differences between the intervention group and the control group.

Analysis.name: Maternal sepsis: subgroup analysis (polypharmacy vs monopharmacy)
Bias.arising.from.the.randomization.proc:
• A double-blind, placebo-controlled randomized trial
  • Women in labour were randomized to receive either a single dose of 2 g of oral azithromycin or placebo (ratio 1:1)
Bias.due.to.deviations.from.intended.int: The active drug and the placebo looked identical. The study clinicians were blind to the treatment allocation. Probably ITT.
Bias.due.to.missing.outcome.data.support: Data was available for all participants randomized.
Bias.in.measurement.of.the.outcome.suppo: Diagnoses were based on clinical judgement according to the study clinicians.
Bias.in.selection.of.the.reported.result: The present study and protocol have slightly different purposes.
Overall.bias.support: The present study and protocol have slightly different purposes.

Analysis.name: Maternal sepsis: subgroup analysis (polypharmacy vs monopharmacy)
Bias.arising.from.the.randomization.proc:
• Participants assignment to intervention (the 'intention-to-treat' effect)
  • Described as 'randomised, double-blind, placebo-controlled trial' 
  • 829 women randomly assigned (1:1)
Bias.due.to.deviations.from.intended.int: "For the primary analysis, all randomized participants were assigned to their randomization group"
Bias.due.to.missing.outcome.data.support: Data was available for most randomized participants.
Bias.in.selection.of.the.reported.result: Data analysis was planned before randomization and performed accordance with prespecified analysis plan.
Overall.bias.support: No concerns about the risk of bias.

Analysis.name: Maternal sepsis: subgroup analysis (polypharmacy vs monopharmacy)
Bias.arising.from.the.randomization.proc: The sequential randomization assignments were computer generated using permuted block sizes of 3, 6, and 9, and were stratified by site.
Bias.due.to.deviations.from.intended.int: Only the investigational pharmacist, responsible for packaging the drug allotments, and the data-coordinating center were aware of treatment assignments. All analyses used the intention-to-treat principle.
Bias.due.to.missing.outcome.data.support: Medical records, postpartum visits or phone call and any readmission.
Bias.in.measurement.of.the.outcome.suppo: Medical records, postpartum visits or phone call and any readmission.
Overall.bias.support: No concerns about the risk of bias.

Analysis.name: Maternal sepsis: subgroup analysis (polypharmacy vs monopharmacy)
Bias.arising.from.the.randomization.proc: "Trial packs of azithromycin and identical placebo were numbered sequentially with the use of a compyter algorithm, which used a predetermined 1:1 randomization schedule for azithromycin and placebo, stratified according to site, and a permuted-block randomization with vaaried block sizes." There was no clear differences between the intervention group and the control group.
Bias.due.to.deviations.from.intended.int: "Each dose consisted of four pills of 500mg of azithromycin or placebo and were labeled with a unique package identifier. Clinicians, research staff members, and patients were unaware of trial-group assignments."" The primary analyses were performed in the intention-to treat population."
Bias.due.to.missing.outcome.data.support: 14589 (99.4%) of 14687 participants at the intervention group and 14687 (99.4%) of 14782 at the control group had side effects data.
Bias.in.selection.of.the.reported.result: They planned analyses methods before unblinded outcome data were available for analyses.
Overall.bias.support: No concerns about the risk of bias.
